        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "GenAI Reference Architectures"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A reference architecture defines the canonical component arrangement for a class of GenAI systems. Choosing the right architecture before writing code prevents rebuilding: a simple chatbot and an autonomous research agent look similar in a demo but have fundamentally different data paths, failure modes, and operational requirements. This sub-subtopic covers the four architectures that cover 90 % of production GenAI use cases, the decision criteria for choosing between them, and the key implementation patterns for each."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Four Architectures"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Four GenAI reference architectures: (1) Prompt-only \u2014 query goes directly to LLM; (2) RAG \u2014 query is embedded, documents retrieved, prompt augmented; (3) Agentic \u2014 LLM plans, calls tools, re-plans; (4) Multi-model routing \u2014 classifier routes to small or large LLM based on query complexity."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture 1: Prompt-Only"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest architecture: the user's query is formatted into a prompt and sent directly to the LLM. There is no retrieval, no tool use, no state. The model's pre-training knowledge is the only source of information."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": tasks where the model's training data is sufficient \u2014 text classification, summarisation, reformatting, translation, code generation from well-specified requirements."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When not to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": anything requiring facts more recent than the training cutoff, private organisational knowledge, or real-time data."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Key design decisions",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": system prompt engineering, output format (JSON vs prose), token budget control, temperature."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from openai import OpenAI\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\nclass ClassificationResult(BaseModel):\n    category: str\n    confidence: float\n    reasoning: str\n\nSYSTEM = \"\"\"You are a customer support ticket classifier.\nClassify the ticket into one of: billing, technical, account, other.\nRespond in JSON with fields: category, confidence (0-1), reasoning.\"\"\"\"\n\ndef classify_ticket(ticket_text: str) -> ClassificationResult:\n    rsp = client.beta.chat.completions.parse(\n        model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": SYSTEM},\n            {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": ticket_text},\n        ],\n        response_format=ClassificationResult,\n        temperature=0,\n    )\n    return rsp.choices[0].message.parsed\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture 2: Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RAG adds a retrieval step before the LLM call: the query is embedded, semantically similar documents are fetched from a vector store, and the retrieved content is inserted into the prompt as context. This grounds the model's response in specific documents and avoids hallucination about domain-specific facts."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": customer support over product documentation, internal Q&A over proprietary knowledge bases, legal or medical document Q&A, news or financial data that changes frequently."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When not to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": tasks with no relevant document corpus; tasks where the retrieved documents would always exceed the context window; tasks that require real-time computation (use agentic with tool calls instead)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Key design decisions",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": chunk size and overlap, embedding model, number of retrieved documents (top-k), re-ranking, citation format in the response."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import List\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n@dataclass\nclass RetrievedChunk:\n    doc_id: str\n    text: str\n    score: float\n\ndef rag_answer(\n    query: str,\n    retrieve_fn,           # (query: str) -> List[RetrievedChunk]\n    model: str = \"gpt-4o\",\n    top_k: int = 5,\n    system_prompt: str = \"Answer based only on the provided context.\",\n) -> str:\n    chunks = retrieve_fn(query)[:top_k]\n\n    context_block = \"\\n\\n\".join(\n        f\"[{i+1}] (doc_id={c.doc_id})\\n{c.text}\"\n        for i, c in enumerate(chunks)\n    )\n    user_message = f\"\"\"Context:\\n{context_block}\\n\\nQuestion: {query}\"\"\"\n\n    rsp = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=model,\n        messages=[\n            {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": system_prompt},\n            {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": user_message},\n        ],\n    )\n    return rsp.choices[0].message.content\n\n# Hybrid retrieval: combine keyword (BM25) and vector scores\ndef hybrid_score(bm25_score: float, vector_score: float, alpha: float = 0.5) -> float:\n    \"\"\"alpha=1 \u2192 pure vector; alpha=0 \u2192 pure keyword.\"\"\\\"\n    return alpha * vector_score + (1 - alpha) * bm25_score\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture 3: Agentic"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In an agentic architecture the LLM acts as a planner that decides which tools to call, interprets the tool results, and decides whether to call more tools or synthesise a final answer. This enables multi-step reasoning over external systems: web search, code execution, database queries, API calls."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": tasks that require gathering information from multiple sources, tasks with conditional branches (\"if the order is shipped, check tracking; otherwise check inventory\"), autonomous research pipelines, coding assistants that need to run and test code."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When not to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": latency-sensitive applications (agent loops add 1\u20135 extra LLM calls per response); tasks with hard safety boundaries (harder to predict execution paths); tasks solvable with a single prompt or RAG retrieval."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Key design decisions",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": tool schema design, maximum re-plan iterations (prevents infinite loops), timeout per tool call, human-in-the-loop checkpoints for high-stakes actions."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import json\nfrom typing import Any\nfrom openai import OpenAI\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n# Tool registry\ndef get_order_status(order_id: str) -> dict:\n    # In production: query order management system\n    return {\"order_id\": order_id, \"status\": \"shipped\", \"tracking\": \"1Z999AA1\"}\n\ndef get_product_info(product_id: str) -> dict:\n    return {\"product_id\": product_id, \"name\": \"Widget Pro\", \"in_stock\": True}\n\nTOOLS = [\n    {\n        \"type\": \"function\",\n        \"function\": {\n            \"name\": \"get_order_status\",\n            \"description\": \"Look up the status of a customer order by order ID.\",\n            \"parameters\": {\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\"order_id\": {\"type\": \"string\"}},\n                \"required\": [\"order_id\"],\n            },\n        },\n    },\n    {\n        \"type\": \"function\",\n        \"function\": {\n            \"name\": \"get_product_info\",\n            \"description\": \"Get current information about a product by product ID.\",\n            \"parameters\": {\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\"product_id\": {\"type\": \"string\"}},\n                \"required\": [\"product_id\"],\n            },\n        },\n    },\n]\n\nTOOL_FNS = {\"get_order_status\": get_order_status, \"get_product_info\": get_product_info}\n\ndef run_agent(user_query: str, max_iterations: int = 5) -> str:\n    messages = [\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"You are a helpful customer support agent.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\",   \"content\": user_query},\n    ]\n    for _ in range(max_iterations):\n        rsp = client.chat.completions.create(\n            model=\"gpt-4o\",\n            messages=messages,\n            tools=TOOLS,\n            tool_choice=\"auto\",\n        )\n        msg = rsp.choices[0].message\n        if not msg.tool_calls:\n            return msg.content    # final answer\n\n        messages.append(msg)\n        for tc in msg.tool_calls:\n            fn = TOOL_FNS[tc.function.name]\n            args = json.loads(tc.function.arguments)\n            result = fn(**args)\n            messages.append({\n                \"role\": \"tool\",\n                \"tool_call_id\": tc.id,\n                \"content\": json.dumps(result),\n            })\n    return \"Max iterations reached without a final answer.\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture 4: Multi-Model Routing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-model routing uses a fast, cheap classifier to assign each request to the cheapest model tier that can handle it adequately. Simple queries (\"what are your business hours?\") go to a small model; complex queries (\"draft a legal summary comparing these two contracts\") go to a large model. At scale, routing can reduce inference cost by 60\u201380 % without measurable quality degradation for simple requests."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": high-volume applications with mixed query complexity; cost-sensitive products where a single large model would be prohibitively expensive at scale."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "When not to use",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": low-volume applications where cost is not a concern; applications where every query requires the full capability of the large model; situations where the routing classifier itself introduces unacceptable latency."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Optional\nfrom openai import OpenAI\nimport re\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\n@dataclass\nclass RoutingDecision:\n    model: str\n    reason: str\n    estimated_complexity: str   # \"low\" | \"medium\" | \"high\"\n\ndef classify_complexity(query: str) -> RoutingDecision:\n    \"\"\"\n    Heuristic-based routing (production systems use a fine-tuned classifier).\n    \"\"\"\n    word_count = len(query.split())\n    has_code = bool(re.search(r\"```|def |class |function\", query))\n    has_comparison = bool(re.search(r\"compar|differ|vs|versus|contrast\", query, re.I))\n    has_multipart = \"and\" in query.lower() and word_count > 30\n\n    if any([has_code, has_comparison, has_multipart, word_count > 80]):\n        return RoutingDecision(\n            model=\"gpt-4o\",\n            reason=\"high complexity\",\n            estimated_complexity=\"high\",\n        )\n    if word_count > 30:\n        return RoutingDecision(\n            model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n            reason=\"medium complexity\",\n            estimated_complexity=\"medium\",\n        )\n    return RoutingDecision(\n        model=\"gpt-4o-mini\",\n        reason=\"low complexity\",\n        estimated_complexity=\"low\",\n    )\n\ndef routed_completion(query: str, system: str = \"\") -> tuple[str, RoutingDecision]:\n    decision = classify_complexity(query)\n    messages = []\n    if system:\n        messages.append({\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": system})\n    messages.append({\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": query})\n    rsp = client.chat.completions.create(model=decision.model, messages=messages)\n    return rsp.choices[0].message.content, decision\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing an Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The decision tree below maps use-case properties to the right architecture. Start from the top and stop at the first matching condition."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Does the task require external actions or multi-step reasoning?",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2192 Architecture 3 (Agentic)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Does the task require private, proprietary, or frequently-updated knowledge?",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2192 Architecture 2 (RAG)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Is the workload high-volume with mixed query complexity and cost is a primary concern?",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2192 Architecture 4 (Multi-model routing)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Otherwise",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2192 Architecture 1 (Prompt-only); add complexity only when the simple architecture demonstrably fails"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Start with Architecture 1. The most common mistake in GenAI system design is choosing a complex architecture before understanding whether a simpler one would work. A prompt-only system is cheaper, faster, easier to debug, and easier to evaluate. Graduate to RAG, Agentic, or Multi-model routing only when you have evidence that the simpler architecture cannot meet the quality or cost requirements."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
