          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Combining Architectures"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Production systems often combine architectures. An agentic system may use RAG as one of its tool calls (\"search the knowledge base\"). A multi-model router may route complex queries to a RAG pipeline rather than a direct LLM call. The reference architectures above are not mutually exclusive \u2014 they are composable building blocks. The key discipline is to make each composition decision explicit and deliberate, and to ensure that the operational complexity of the combined system is justified by a measured quality or cost benefit."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The four GenAI reference architectures \u2014 Prompt-only, RAG, Agentic, and Multi-model routing \u2014 cover the vast majority of production use cases. Prompt-only is the default starting point; RAG adds grounding when proprietary or fresh knowledge is needed; Agentic enables multi-step reasoning and tool use when the task cannot be answered from a single context; Multi-model routing optimises cost when query complexity varies widely at scale. Choosing the simplest architecture that meets the requirements, and graduating complexity only with evidence, is the core principle of sound GenAI system design."
          }
        ]
      }
